Apart from his morality Juvenal was a great master of words, and had a large fund of illustration. His pictures drawn from real life, as I have observed in the course of the notes, are particularly happy: whether they represent the common room of a tavern, or the deok of 'a ship, or the inside o'f a soldier's hut or of a camp, or a schoolroom, or the greedy crowd at the sportula, or the streets of Rome, or a drun'ken 'brawl‚ these a'nd a hundred other soenes are so drawn that an ortist would have no difficulty in transferring 'them tocanvas. But his hand mustbe vigorous and his brush free, or he would do no justice to Juvenal.
